,"nameMeanings":[{"name":"Leake","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Leake (Lincolnshire), East and West Leake (Nottinghamshire), Leek (Staffordshire), Leck (Lancashire), Leak (NorthYorkshire), or Leak Hall in Cumberworth (West Yorkshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>lece</i> or Old Scandinavian <i>lœkr</i>, both meaning ‘brook’. See also   Like  .","possibly also a nickname from Middle English <i>lek</i> ‘leek’ (Old English <i>lēac</i>), perhaps for a grower or seller of leeks."],"variants":[{"name":"League","meanings":["English (Hereford and Worcester): perhaps a variant of   Leake  ."]},{"name":"Like","meanings":["Probably a variant of   Lyke   1, a surname of Flemish origin.","English: probably a variant of   Leake   rather than a nickname from Middle English <i>lik</i> ‘similar, alike, equal’, which is not recorded as a personal epithet. This surname is rare in Britain. See also   Lyke   2."]},{"name":"Leck","meanings":["English: variant of   Leake  .","North German: habitational name from a place so named in Schleswig-Holstein.","North German: possibly also an altered form of   Lech  ."]},{"name":"Leak","meanings":["English: variant of   Leake  ."]},{"name":"Leeke","meanings":["English (northern): variant of   Leake  ."]},{"name":"Leeks","meanings":["English (northern): variant of   Leake  ."]},{"name":"Leek","meanings":["English: variant of   Leake  .","Dutch (also <b>Van der Leek</b>): topographic name for someone living near a water named Leek (North Holland), from <i>leek</i> ‘border water’. Compare   Laack   2."]},{"name":"Leaks","meanings":["English: variant of   Leake  ."]}]},{"name":"III","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Yuko, Aiko, Hideaki, Hiroki, Hiroyuki, Isamu, Kaoru, Katsumi, Keiichiro, Kenji, Masako, Masayuki.","Japanese: variously written, sometimes with characters used phonetically; the most probable meanings are 仁井 ‘benevolent well’, 新居 ‘new residence’, or 新井 ‘new well’. It is not common in Japan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":4,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":29,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs John Leake III was born from 8 January 1285 to 7 January 1286. She married Sir John Leke III in 1315, in Nottinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1315, in Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England."},"et":{"1285–AFT 1315":"8. jaanuar 1285 kuni 7. jaanuar 1286–pärast 1315","1282–1320":"1282–1320","1308–1334":"1308–1334","1285–1315":"8.jaanuar1285kuni7.jaanuar1286–1315","1315":"1315","1334":"1334","AFT 1315":"pärast 1315","1320":"1320","1285":"8. jaanuar 1285 kuni 7. jaanuar 1286","1282":"1282","1308":"1308","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1285–AFT 1315":"vuodesta 8. tammikuuta 1285 vuoteen 7. tammikuuta 1286–1315 jälkeen","1282–1320":"1282–1320","1308–1334":"1308–1334","1285–1315":"vuodesta8.tammikuuta1285vuoteen7.tammikuuta1286–1315","1315":"1315","1334":"1334","AFT 1315":"1315 jälkeen","1320":"1320","1285":"vuodesta 8. tammikuuta 1285 vu